  "prompt": "Why does iOS still regularly demand a passcode, when a fingerprint is surely more secure?",
  "response": "Even though fingerprint authentication is quite secure, there are several reasons why iOS devices still regularly require a passcode:\n\n1. **Fail-safe Mechanism**: If the device fails to recognize the fingerprint multiple times (typically after 5 attempts), it will require the passcode to ensure that unauthorized users aren't trying to access the device repeatedly.\n\n2. **Device Restart**: After the device has restarted or powered off, it will require the passcode to activate and decrypt the device before allowing fingerprint authentication.\n\n3. **Time Elapsed**: iOS mandates that a passcode must be entered periodically, typically after 48 hours without unlocking the device, to confirm the user's identity.\n\n4. **Background Security Check**: Some secure transactions or changes to security settings require the passcode as an additional layer of authentication beyond fingerprint recognition.\n\n5. **New Fingerprint Addition**: Any time new fingerprints are added to the device, the passcode is required to verify the identity of the user making these changes.\n\n6. **System Updates**: When major system updates or patches are installed, the passcode is required post-update to confirm the user\u2019s identity.\n\nBy requiring a passcode periodically, iOS enhances security and ensures ongoing verification of the authorized user in scenarios where fingerprint recognition might not suffice by itself.",
